properties.description: Maps data to the Banner and Location tables

scriptLines: {Gross area owned stores ft2} as integer,
{Sales area owned stores ft2} as integer
Charge split(case(    Banner == "Giant", true(),     Banner == "Stop and Shop", true()),
Leakage split(case(    Banner == "SS", true(),     Banner == "GF", true()),
joinSSGF filter(BannerName == "Stop and Shop"|| BannerName == "Giant") ~> filterSSGF
joinRest filter(BannerName != "Stop and Shop" && BannerName != "Giant") ~> filterRest
join2 filter(BannerName!= "Stop and Shop" && BannerName != "Giant") ~> filter1
VirtualEmissionFactorData derive({virtual Location based} = replace({virtual Location based},',','.'),
{virtual Market based} = replace({virtual Market based},',','.')) ~> CommaToPoint
CommaToPoint derive({virtual Market based} = toDouble({virtual Market based}),
{virtual Location based} = toDouble({virtual Location based})) ~> FromTextToInt

content.query:
IF NOT EXISTS (SELECT * FROM sys.external_file_formats WHERE name = 'SynapseDelimitedTextFormat') 
	CREATE EXTERNAL FILE FORMAT [SynapseDelimitedTextFormat] 
	WITH ( FORMAT_TYPE = DELIMITEDTEXT ,
	       FORMAT_OPTIONS (
			 FIELD_TERMINATOR = ',',
			 USE_TYPE_DEFAULT = FALSE
			))
GO

IF NOT EXISTS (SELECT * FROM sys.external_data_sources WHERE name = 'fsgdmsdevweeu01_stgdmsdevweeu01_dfs_core_windows_net') 
	CREATE EXTERNAL DATA SOURCE [fsgdmsdevweeu01_stgdmsdevweeu01_dfs_core_windows_net] 
	WITH (
		LOCATION = 'abfss://fsgdmsdevweeu01@stgdmsdevweeu01.dfs.core.windows.net' 
	)
GO

CREATE EXTERNAL TABLE [Emission] (
	[Country] nvarchar(4000),
	[CarbonScope] nvarchar(4000),
	[EmissionCategory] nvarchar(4000),
	[EmissionType] nvarchar(4000),
	[EmissionFactorLocationBased] float,
	[EmissionFactorMarketBased] float,
	[UnitOfMeasure] nvarchar(4000),
	[StartDate] date,
	[EndDate] date,
	[Region] nvarchar(4000),
	[HasMarketBasedFactor] bigint
	)
	WITH (
	LOCATION = 'ESG_staging/EmissionFactors.csv',
	DATA_SOURCE = [fsgdmsdevweeu01_stgdmsdevweeu01_dfs_core_windows_net],
	FILE_FORMAT = [SynapseDelimitedTextFormat]
	)
GO


SELECT TOP 100 * FROM [dbo].[Emission]
GO

NewEntity.Name: BrandCategory
NewEntity.Description:
An organization-defined classification or categorization of products or services that address the same consumer needs and have similar attributes and benefits.

The Brand Category most likely corresponds to some generic division of products in the Product family such as "toothpaste", "deodorant", "vitamin supplements"...

There are three Product branding strategies:

1.  Individual branding, which creates individual brand names and identities for each Product.

2.  Family branding, which uses the same brand name for two or more products.

3.  Combination branding, which enables products to carry both family brand names and individual brand names.   Breakfast cereals often utilize this approach.

A brand is name, term, sign, symbol or design or a combination of these which identify the goods or services and differentiate them from those of competitors' 

A Trade mark is a brand or some part of the brand that is given legal protection because it is capable of exclusive appropriation and representation.

Manufacturers can use their own brands (known as Manufacturers' brands) or brands of their distributors (Distributors' brands). 

Manufacturers/ distributors use brand names for a variety of reasons ranging from simple identification purposes to having legal protection for unique features of the products from imitations.

Brands help consumers recognize certain quality parameters. In some cases, brands are just used to endow the product with unique story and character which itself can be a basis for product differentiation. 

Individual brand have their own identity and the corporate or common name is not used to promote its equity. 

Individual branding requires more expensive advertising and brand extensive brand creation investments..  By extension, each new brand does not benefit from the positive perceptions of earlier brands.

By contrast, family branding has several advantages.

Each new product is quickly associated with the other products and brand in terms of quality and benefits.

Reduced or eliminated time for name identification and advertising for name recognition purposes.

Columns.Name: BrandCategoryId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Brand Category.

Columns.Name: BrandCategoryName
Columns.Description: The name of the Brand Category.

Columns.Name: BrandCategoryDescription
Columns.Description: The description of the Brand Category.

NewEntity.Name: EmissionWasteType
NewEntity.Description:
The type of emission waste:

Ex:
- cardboard
- food waste
- waste water
- solid waste
- third-party disposal waste

Emissions from waste depend on the type of waste being disposed of, and the waste diversion method. 

Companies should collect:

- Waste type-specific and waste treatment-specific emission factors. The emission factors should include end-of-life processes only. Emission factors may include emissions from transportation of waste.

NewEntity.Name: Ingredient
NewEntity.Description:
Any material, including additives, used during the production or preparation of a product and which are still present in the finished product, even if in altered form. 

Like a recipe, the ingredient list defines what is in the package. 
If a product contains more than one ingredient, the label must list all ingredients in descending order by percentage of the total weight of the contents they comprise. This means that the ingredient in the largest amount must be listed first and the ingredient present in the least amount must be listed last.

Columns.Name: IngredientId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of an Ingredient.

Columns.Name: IngredientName
Columns.Description: The name of an Ingredient.

Columns.Name: IngredientDescription
Columns.Description: The description of an Ingredient.

Columns.Name: OrganicIngredientIndicator
Columns.Description: Organics include substances that contain carbon bonded to hydrogen.

Columns.Name: InorganicIngredientIndicator
Columns.Description: Inorganics include salts, metals, substances made from single elements and any other compounds that don't contain carbon bonded to hydrogen.

Columns.Name: CasNumber
Columns.Description: Chemical Abstracts Service Registry Number is a unique identifier for a chemical and its synonyms. CAS numbers identify the chemical, but not its concentration or specific mixture.

Columns.Name: ItemSku
Columns.Description: The Stock Keeping Unit identifier, which is typically used for inventory-related activities.

NewEntity.Name: ItemPackagingItem
NewEntity.Description:
Indicates the number of an item (SKU) that are used in the packaging of the Product.

Note: This contains packaging and supplementary items such as documentation, coupons and free items but does not include any base product items.

Note: Changes  in packaging does not necessarily result in a changed GTIN, UPC, etc. The following are a few of the many examples where a new GTIN, UPC, etc. would be required for the packaged product:
- change of over 20% to a physical dimension, on any axis, or gross weight
- change in the case or pallet orientation (even when there is no change in the base product)
- change in the number of base products included on the pallet
- free trial item included even though this does not change the GTIN, UPC, etc. of the base product

Columns.Name: GlobalLocationNumber
Columns.Description: The Global Location Number (GLN) is a simple tool used to uniquely identify locations. It can be used to identify physical locations such as a warehouse, legal entities, or a function / department within a legal entity. The GLN is part of the GS1 system of standards.

Columns.Name: DunsNumber
Columns.Description: The DUNS number is a nine-digit number issued by Dun & Bradstreet and assigned to each business location in the D&B database having a unique, separate, and distinct operation to businesses for the purpose of identifying them. The number as issued is random and the digits apparently have no significance as to their issuance.

Columns.Name: DunBradstreetSingleLocationSubsidiary
Columns.Description:
There are eight (8) types of business relationships defined in D&B WorldBase:

Single Location Subsidiary

A single location subsidiary has reporting responsibilities to its parent; however, it does not have branches or subsidiaries reporting to it. Do not confuse this with a stand-alone business which is titled "single location" and is not part of a corporate family.

Headquarters

A headquarters is a business establishment that has branches or divisions reporting to it, and is financially responsible for those branches or divisions. If the headquarters is more that 50% owned by another corporation, it also will be a subsidiary. If it owns more that 50% of another corporation, then it is also a parent.

Branch

A branch is a secondary location of its headquarters. It has no legal responsibility for its debts, even though bills may be paid from the branch location. It will have the same legal business name as its headquarters, although branches frequently operate under a different trade style than the headquarters establishment. A branch may be located at the same address as the headquarters if it has a unique trade style. In such cases, the branch may appear to be a duplicate with a different D-U-N-S number than the headquarters record, which may confuse customers if they don't purchase the trade style field.

Division

A division, like a branch, is a secondary location of a business. However, a division carries out specific business operations related to the headquarters under a divisional name. Divisions look similar to branches in D&B WorldBase and carry a branch code.

Subsidiary

A subsidiary is a corporation that is more than 50% owned by another corporation and will have a different legal business name from its parent company. A subsidiary may have branches and/or subsidiaries of its own. If it does, then its D-U-N-S Number appears in the headquarter/parent D-U-N-S Number field of its children.

Parent

A parent is a corporation that owns more than 50 percent of another corporation. The parent company also may be a subsidiary of another corporation. If the parent also has branches, then it is also a headquarters.

Domestic Ultimate

The Domestic Ultimate is a subsidiary within the global family tree which is the highest ranking member within a specific country.

Global Ultimate

The Global Ultimate is the top most responsible entity within the global family tree. The Global Ultimate may have branches and/or subsidiaries reporting directly or indirectly to it.

NewEntity.Name: MasterRecipe
NewEntity.Description:
A master recipe is targeted to a processing area and is derived from either a general or site recipe. 

Master recipes depend on equipment types or classes

These recipes can contain product-specific information required for detailed scheduling, such as equipment requirements. 

A master recipe is the template for recipes used to create individual batches. Without this template, no specific batch recipes can be created, and therefore, no batches can be produced.

Columns.Name: RecipeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a recipe.

A master recipe is targeted to a processing area and is derived from either a general or site recipe. 

Master recipes depend on equipment types or classes

These recipes can contain product-specific information required for detailed scheduling, such as equipment requirements. 

A master recipe is the template for recipes used to create individual batches. Without this template, no specific batch recipes can be created, and therefore, no batches can be produced.

NewEntity.Name: Order
NewEntity.Description: A document or commission by the customer to order products. Could be a silly order.

Columns.Name: OrderId
Columns.Description: The unique number that identifies an Order.

Columns.Name: OrderConfirmationNumber
Columns.Description: The order confirmation number provided to the Customer/Customer Account.

Columns.Name: OrderEnteredByEmployeeId
Columns.Description: The employee ID of the employee entering the Order into the order entry system.

Columns.Name: NumberOfOrderLines
Columns.Description: The number of Order Line Items associated with the Order.

Columns.Name: OrderReceivedTimestamp
Columns.Description: The timestamp that the Order was received from the Customer/Customer Account.

Columns.Name: OrderEntryTimestamp
Columns.Description: The date that the Order was entered into the order entry system.

Columns.Name: CustomerCreditCheckTimestamp
Columns.Description: The timestamp that the Customer/Customer Account had a credit check in regard to the Order amount.

Columns.Name: OrderConfirmationTimestamp
Columns.Description: The timestamp that the Order was confirmed to the Customer/Customer Account.

Columns.Name: OrderRequestedDeliveryDate
Columns.Description: The date that the Customer/Customer Account requested delivery of the Order.

Columns.Name: OrderCommittedDeliveryDate
Columns.Description: The date committed to the Customer/Customer Account for delivery of the Order.

Columns.Name: ShipmentConfirmationTimestamp
Columns.Description: The timestamp that confirmation of the Shipment was made to the Customer/Customer Account.

Columns.Name: OrderActualDeliveryTimestamp
Columns.Description: The actual timestamp of delivery of the Order to the Customer/Customer Account.

Columns.Name: OrderTotalRetailPriceAmount
Columns.Description: The total list price value of the ordered products = (list price per unit product price)x(quantity ordered) for each line item.

Columns.Name: OrderTotalActualSalesPriceAmount
Columns.Description: The total actual price value of the ordered products = (actual selling price per unit product price)x(quantity ordered) for each line item.

Columns.Name: OrderTotalAdjustmentPercentage
Columns.Description: The total percentage of adjustment applied to the Order.

Columns.Name: OrderTotalAdjustmentAmount
Columns.Description: The total amount of adjustment applied to the Order.

Columns.Name: OrderTotalAmount
Columns.Description: The total value of the Order including Adjustment(s).

Columns.Name: TotalShippingChargeAmount
Columns.Description: The total amount of shipping charge associated with the order.

Columns.Name: OrderTotalTaxAmount
Columns.Description: The total amount of all taxes applied to the Order.

Columns.Name: OrderTotalInvoicedAmount
Columns.Description: The total invoiced amount to the Customer/Customer Account = (per units selling price of products)x(quantity purchased) for all line items + all discounts + all rebates + adjustments/credits + taxes

Columns.Name: TotalGratuityAmount
Columns.Description: The total amount of gratuity paid.

Columns.Name: TotalPaidAmount
Columns.Description: The total amount including gratuity.

Columns.Name: TotalCommissionsPayableAmount
Columns.Description: The total amount of commissions payable and due in regard to the Order.

Columns.Name: SplitCommissionsIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the commissions are to be split between two or more employees.

Columns.Name: OrderBookedDate
Columns.Description: The date signifying that the order has all the needed information to be considered a firm order and to be processed.

Columns.Name: OrderBilledDate
Columns.Description: The date that the Order was billed.

Columns.Name: OrderBacklogReportedDate
Columns.Description: The date that the Order backlog was reported.

Columns.Name: OrderBacklogReleasedDate
Columns.Description: The date that the Order backlog was released/fulfilled.

Columns.Name: OrderCancellationDate
Columns.Description: The date that the Order was cancelled.

Columns.Name: OrderReturnedDate
Columns.Description: The date that the Order was returned.

Columns.Name: ShipmentToName
Columns.Description: The name of the ship-to party.

Columns.Name: ShipmentToLocationId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Location.

Columns.Name: ShipmentId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Shipment.

Columns.Name: CarrierId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Carrier.

Columns.Name: ShipmentMethodId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Shipment Method.

Columns.Name: RequestedShipmentCarrierName
Columns.Description: The name of the Carrier for the Shipment requested by the Customer/Customer Account.

Columns.Name: AlternateCarrierAcceptableIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that an alternate Carrier of the Shipment would be acceptable to the Customer/Customer Account.

Columns.Name: ActualShipmentCarrierName
Columns.Description: The Carrier of the Shipment.

Columns.Name: ShipOrderCompleteIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the Order is only to be shipped when complete - no partial shipments.

Columns.Name: TotalOrderWeight
Columns.Description: The total weight of the Order.

Columns.Name: WeightUomId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Unit Of Measure.

Columns.Name: TotalOrderFreightChargeAmount
Columns.Description: The total order freight charges amount.

Columns.Name: EarliestDeliveryWindowTimestamp
Columns.Description: The earliest timestamp that the order should be made available for delivery.

Columns.Name: LatestDeliveryWindowTimestamp
Columns.Description: The latest timestamp that the order should be made available for delivery.

Columns.Name: AcknowledgementRequiredIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that an acknowledgement  to the Customer/Customer Account is required for the Order.

Columns.Name: ExpediteOrderIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the Order is to be expedited.

Columns.Name: DropShipmentIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the Order is to be drop shipped.

Columns.Name: ServiceOrderIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the Order is for Service Products.

Columns.Name: ProductOrderIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the Order is for Products.

Columns.Name: OrderDeliveryInstructions
Columns.Description: Instructions related to the delivery of the Order.

Columns.Name: CustomerCreditCheckNote
Columns.Description: A note, comment or additional information regarding the Order credit check.

Columns.Name: MessageToCustomer
Columns.Description: A message to the Customer/Customer Account regarding the Order.

Columns.Name: CustomerId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Customer.

Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Promotion Offer. The Promotion Offer ID is unique to each account or party that is offered to.

Columns.Name: ItemSku
Columns.Description: The Stock Keeping Unit identifier, which is typically used for inventory-related activities.

Columns.Name: Quantity
Columns.Description: The quantity of Product ordered on the order line item.

Columns.Name: ProductListPriceAmount
Columns.Description: The current per unit list price of the Order Line Item products.

Columns.Name: ProductSalesPriceAmount
Columns.Description: The actual per unit selling price of the Order Line Item products.

Columns.Name: ProductAdjustmentAmount
Columns.Description: The per product unit adjustment amount applied to each product unit.

Columns.Name: ProductAdjustmentPercentage
Columns.Description: The per product unit adjustment percentage applied to each product unit.

Columns.Name: TotalOrderLineAdjustmentAmount
Columns.Description: The amount of adjustment for all order line items.

Columns.Name: TotalOrderLineAmount
Columns.Description: The total amount of line item charges related to the quantity of products sold at the actual selling price less rebates and discounts.

Columns.Name: OrderLineNote
Columns.Description: A note, comment or additional information regarding the Order Line.

Columns.Name: QuantityBooked
Columns.Description: The quantity of Product booked.

Columns.Name: QuantityBilled
Columns.Description: The quantity billed.

Columns.Name: QuantityBacklog
Columns.Description: The quantity on backlog.

Columns.Name: AcceptedQuantity
Columns.Description: The quantity of Order Line Item products accepted.

Columns.Name: QuantityCancelled
Columns.Description: The quantity of Order Line Items cancelled.

Columns.Name: QuantityReturned
Columns.Description: The quantity of Order Line Items returned.

Columns.Name: BookedDate
Columns.Description: The booked date of the Order Line Items.

Columns.Name: BilledDate
Columns.Description: The billed date of the Order Line Items.

Columns.Name: CancelledTimestamp
Columns.Description: The date  and time that Order Line Items were cancelled.

Columns.Name: ReturnedDate
Columns.Description: The date that Order Line Items were returned.

Columns.Name: RequestedDeliveryDate
Columns.Description: The date for delivery of the Order Line Item requested by the Customer/Customer Account.

Columns.Name: CommittedDeliveryDate
Columns.Description: The date committed for delivery of the Order Line Item.

Columns.Name: PlannedPickDate
Columns.Description: The planned inventory pick date for the Order Line Items.

Columns.Name: ActualPickTimestamp
Columns.Description: The actual inventory pick timestamp for the Order Line Items.

Columns.Name: PlannedShipmentDate
Columns.Description: The planned shipment date of the Order Line Items.

Columns.Name: ActualShipmentTimestamp
Columns.Description: The actual shipment timestamp of the Order Line Items.

Columns.Name: PlannedDeliveryDate
Columns.Description: The planned delivery date of the Order Line Items.

Columns.Name: ActualDeliveryTimestamp
Columns.Description: The actual delivery timestamp of the Order Line Items.

Columns.Name: ShipmentConfirmationTimestamp
Columns.Description: The timestamp that the shipment confirmation notice was sent to the Customer/Customer Account.

Columns.Name: DropShipOrderLineItemIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the Order Line Item(s) are to be drop shipped.

Columns.Name: WaybillNumber
Columns.Description: The shipment waybill number.

Columns.Name: TareWeight
Columns.Description: The weight of the line items excluding packaging.

Columns.Name: NetWeight
Columns.Description: The weight of the line items including packaging.

Columns.Name: WeightUomId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Unit Of Measure.

Columns.Name: EarliestDeliveryWindowTimestamp
Columns.Description: The earliest timestamp that the order should be made available for delivery.

Columns.Name: LatestDeliveryWindowTimestamp
Columns.Description: The latest timestamp that the order should be made available for delivery.

Columns.Name: ReturnOrderId
Columns.Description: The unique number that identifies an Order.

Columns.Name: ReturnOrderLineNumber
Columns.Description: The number that identifies the Order Line Item.

Columns.Name: ReturnToStockIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the Line Item(s) were returned to stock.

Columns.Name: ReturnToStoreIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the Line Item(s) were returned to the store from which they were purchased.

NewEntity.Name: OrderType
NewEntity.Description:
A categorization of Orders based upon the time when they are to be fulfilled.

Ex:

ADVANCE ORDER
A sales order that is placed far in advance of the requested delivery date.

The buyer typically receives a discount when placing an Advance Order.

Often times Advanced Orders are placed when demand is low, which encourages the seller to grant a larger discount.

CURRENT ORDER
An Order that can be filled immediately because inventory is available.

BACK ORDER
An Order that cannot be filled due to lack of inventory and must be filled when inventory is available.

NewEntity.Name: PackagedItemRelatedItem
NewEntity.Description:
Indicates the number of an item (SKU) that are used in the packaging of the Item.

Note: This contains packaging and supplementary items such as documentation, coupons and free items but does not include any base product items.

Note: Changes  in packaging does not necessarily result in a changed GTIN, UPC, etc. The following are a few of the many examples where a new GTIN, UPC, etc. would be required for the packaged product:
- change of over 20% to a physical dimension, on any axis, or gross weight
- change in the case or pallet orientation (even when there is no change in the base product)
- change in the number of base products included on the pallet
- free trial item included even though this does not change the GTIN, UPC, etc. of the base product

NewEntity.Name: PackagingHierarchyLevelType
NewEntity.Description:
The type of packaging hierarchy level.

Ex:
- Base Unit
- Pack or Inner Pack
- Multipack
- Setpack
- Case
- Display Shipper
- Pallet
- Mixed Module
- Transport Load

where:
Base Unit: The lowest level of the item hierarch intended or labeled for individual resale. For example, an individual box of Kleenex.

Pack or Inner Pack: A logistical unit or a consumer unit between a cash and each. For example, a single GTIN that includes two toothpaste tubes.

Multipack: A group of items (not necessarily the same) that are intended to be sold as a single consumer unit. For example, a three-pack of chocolate bars, each one different.

Setpack: A consumer unit that contains multiple instances of lower level items.

Case: A standard trade item shipping unit. 

Display Shipper: A display which can contain a single or multiple GTINs. 

Pallet: A unit load that contains a single or multiple GTINs that is not display ready. Includes a box pallet.

Mixed Module: A unit load that is a display ready pallet that may contain one or more GTINs that are intended to go directly to the selling floor.

Transport Load: The trade item above the pallet level used for transporting trade items. This level can be used to define truckloads, shipping containers, rail cars, ships and other forms of mass transportation.

NewEntity.Name: ProductPackagingItem
NewEntity.Description:
Indicates the number of an item (SKU) that are used in the packaging of the Product.

Note: This contains packaging and supplementary items such as documentation, coupons and free items but does not include any base product items.

Note: Changes  in packaging does not necessarily result in a changed GTIN, UPC, etc. The following are a few of the many examples where a new GTIN, UPC, etc. would be required for the packaged product:
- change of over 20% to a physical dimension, on any axis, or gross weight
- change in the case or pallet orientation (even when there is no change in the base product)
- change in the number of base products included on the pallet
- free trial item included even though this does not change the GTIN, UPC, etc. of the base product

where:

AAA
Pallet, Returnable
Pallet, Returnable

BAG
Bag
Bag: A preformed,  flexible container, generally enclosed on all but one side, which forms an opening that may or may not be sealed after  filling.
BAL
Bale
Bale

BIN
Bin
Bin

BLK
Bulk
Bulk

BOX
Box
Box: A non-specific term used to refer to a rigid, three-dimensional container with closed faces that completely enclose its contents and may be made out of any material. Even though some boxes might be reused or become resealed they could also be disposable depending on the product hierarchy.

BSK
Basket or hamper
Basket or hamper: A semi rigid container usually open at the top traditionally used for gathering, shipping and marketing agricultural products.

BXI
Box, with inner container
Box, with inner container (e.g., tri-wall)

CAS
Case
Case: A non-specific term for a container designed to hold, house, and sheath or encase its content while protecting it during distribution, storage and/or exhibition. Cases are mostly intended to store and preserve its contents during the product's entire lifetime.

CMS
Clamshell
Clamshell

CNF
Container, Multi-walled, Secured to Warehouse Pallet
Container, Multi-walled, Secured to Warehouse Pallet; e.g., watermelon bin

CNT
Container
Container

CRF
Corner Reinforcement
Corner Reinforcement: Usually in boxes or crates, additional material or components attached to adjacent panels to add support or prevent crushing or separation

CRT
Crate
Crate: A non-specific term usually referring to a rigid three-dimensional container with semi-closed faces that enclose its contents for shipment or storage. Crates could have an open or closed top and may have internal divers. Even though some crates might be reused or become resealed they could also be disposable depending on the product hierarchy.

CTN
Carton
Carton: A non-specific term for a re-closable container used mostly for perishable foods (e.g., eggs, fruit).

CU
Cup
Cup: A small bowl shaped container for beverages, often with a handle.
GNT
Net
Net: A container of meshwork material made from threads or strips twisted or woven to form a regular pattern with spaces between the threads that is used for holding, carrying, trapping, or confining something.

GPB
Pallet Box
Pallet Box: A three-dimensional container which either has a pallet platform permanently attached at its base or alternatively requires a platform for its handling and storage as due to its constitution it cannot be handled without it. The characteristics of the platform should be specified using the pallet type code list.

GPU
Packed, Unspecified
Packed, Unspecified: Packaging of the product (or products) is currently not on the list. Use this code when no suitable options are available and only while a Change Request is approved for the proper packaging type.

JAR
Jar
Jar: A rigid container made of glass, stone, earthenware, plastic or other appropriate material with a large opening, which is used to store products, (e.g., jams, cosmetics).

Loose

Lug

Multipack

Pieces

Plastic-Wrapped Tray

Sack
Sack

SCS

Suitcase

SLV
Sleeve
Sleeve: A non-rigid container usually made of paper, cardboard or plastic, that is open-ended and is slid over the contents for protection or presentation.

SRW
Shrink Wrap
Shrink Wrap: In packaging, a plastic  film around an item or group of items which is heated causing the  film to shrink, securing the unit integrity. The use of shrunken  film to tightly wrap a package or a unit load in order to bind, protect and immobilize it for further handling or shipping.

TBN
Tote Bin
Tote Bin

TRY
Tray
Tray: A shallow container, which may or may not have a cover, used for displaying or carrying items; e.g.,  at.

TUB
Tub
Tub: Generally, a round  at-bottomed container closed with a large lid, typically used to contain ice cream, margarine, sour cream, confections, and other products.

UNP
Unpacked
Unpacked: The item is provided without packaging.

UVQ
Wrapped in Plastic
Wrapped in Plastic

WRP
Wrapped
Wrapped: The process of enclosing all or part of an item with layers of  flexible wrapping material (e.g., for an individually packed ice cream). Does not include items which are shrink-wrapped or vacuum-packed.

AAA

BAG
Bag
Bag: A preformed,  flexible container, generally enclosed on all but one side, which forms an opening that may or may not be sealed after  filling.
BAL
Bale
Bale

BIN
Bin
Bin

BLK
Bulk
Bulk

BOX
Box
Box: A non-specific term used to refer to a rigid, three-dimensional container with closed faces that completely enclose its contents and may be made out of any material. Even though some boxes might be reused or become resealed they could also be disposable depending on the product hierarchy.

BSK
Basket or hamper
Basket or hamper: A semi rigid container usually open at the top traditionally used for gathering, shipping and marketing agricultural products.

BXI
Box, with inner container
Box, with inner container (e.g., tri-wall)

CAS
Case
Case: A non-specific term for a container designed to hold, house, and sheath or encase its content while protecting it during distribution, storage and/or exhibition. Cases are mostly intended to store and preserve its contents during the product's entire lifetime.

CMS
Clamshell
Clamshell

CNF
Container, Multi-walled, Secured to Warehouse Pallet
Container, Multi-walled, Secured to Warehouse Pallet; e.g., watermelon bin

CNT
Container
Container

CRF
Corner Reinforcement
Corner Reinforcement: Usually in boxes or crates, additional material or components attached to adjacent panels to add support or prevent crushing or separation

CRT
Crate
Crate: A non-specific term usually referring to a rigid three-dimensional container with semi-closed faces that enclose its contents for shipment or storage. Crates could have an open or closed top and may have internal divers. Even though some crates might be reused or become resealed they could also be disposable depending on the product hierarchy.

CTN
Carton
Carton: A non-specific term for a re-closable container used mostly for perishable foods (e.g., eggs, fruit).

CU
Cup
Cup: A small bowl shaped container for beverages, often with a handle.
GNT
Net
Net: A container of meshwork material made from threads or strips twisted or woven to form a regular pattern with spaces between the threads that is used for holding, carrying, trapping, or confining something.

GPB
Pallet Box
Pallet Box: A three-dimensional container which either has a pallet platform permanently attached at its base or alternatively requires a platform for its handling and storage as due to its constitution it cannot be handled without it. The characteristics of the platform should be specified using the pallet type code list.

GPU
Packed, Unspecified
Packed, Unspecified: Packaging of the product (or products) is currently not on the list. Use this code when no suitable options are available and only while a Change Request is approved for the proper packaging type.

JAR
Jar
Jar: A rigid container made of glass, stone, earthenware, plastic or other appropriate material with a large opening, which is used to store products, (e.g., jams, cosmetics).

KTB

NewEntity.Name: RecipeResultingIngredients
NewEntity.Description:
The ingredients that the recipe results in.

Note: that the ingredients used may differ from the resulting ingredients in volume or weight.

Columns.Name: RecipeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a recipe.

Columns.Name: IngredientId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of an Ingredient.

Columns.Name: SubstituteIngredientIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates whether the recipe resulting ingredients may have used the ingredient as a substitute or alternate for another ingredient.

Columns.Name: MayContainIngredientIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates whether the recipe resulting ingredients may contain the ingredient. This is usually as a result of the ingredient being used elsewhere in the manufacturing facility and it may have come in contact with the production process. Commonly used for items such as peanuts where some individuals are highly allergic.

NewEntity.Name: RecipeType
NewEntity.Description:
There are different types of recipes to serve different requirements in the organization.

Different parts of a company may require different types of information about a product or the process to manufacture it. 

The R&D group is focused upon the properties of a product and general processing procedures necessary to make it, but do not care exactly what specific equipment is used.

An engineering group tasked with creating a process to manufacture a product may be very focused on the type of equipment used, but not the specific piece of equipment used to make a batch.

A Manufacturer Facility production team is concerned with what specific pieces of equipment are available to make a batch.

Each of these scenarios requires a different type of information and extra information would be confusing.

There are four types of recipes:
- General 
- Master
- Control
- Site

NewEntity.Name: RetailProduct
NewEntity.Description:
A product is anything that can be offered to a market that might satisfy a want or need by potential customers.    That product is the sum of all physical, psychological, symbolic, and service attributes associated with it.

There are two basic types of products:

- Tangible (physical)
- Intangible (non-physical) such as services

A service is a non-material or intangible product - such as professional consultancy, maintenance service, repair service etc.
Each product has its own benefits, application, brand name, and packaging that gives it its own identity and distinguishing characteristics.

Every business or organization has business rules that define precisely what a product is.    While we intuitively know what a product is, we must quantify that knowledge and associated business rules with consistent definitions that can be implemented within the organization in strategies and applications.

A product typically goes through five stages of development:

(1) Idea Stage - involving a thorough evaluation of the potential product

(2) Concept Stage - determines customer acceptance by testing and presentation to consumers and distribution channel members.   Specific aspects regarding quality, dependability, reliability, warranty, packaging, service, pricing, terms of sale, sales and distribution channels, advertising and promotions are evaluated.

(3) Product Development Stage - transforms the prototype product into an actual product for mass sale.   This stage requires close interaction between both marketing and manufacturing.

(4) Test Marketing Stage - may or may not be used since it is an expensive and time-consuming process.  Test marketing involves evaluating various product options and alternatives.

(5) Commercialization - It is very expensive to launch a new product so commercialization only applies to those specific products that are actually going to be sold to the market.

Products tend to be categorized as either:  Industrial goods and consumer goods

Industrial goods are used to produce other products .

Industrial goods may be further divided into:

- Raw materials
- Equipment
- Pre-built materials 
- Supplies.

Consumer goods are intended for consumption by the general public.

Consumer goods may be further divided into:

- Durable goods
- Nondurable goods
- Packaged goods

A product may be a member of a product family or product line.

A product family is a grouping of products or services that are related to each other by common function, functionality, design platform or similar characteristics.

Members of a product family frequently have many common parts and assemblies.

Product families are the highest level of grouping for forecasting, capacity planning or related functions.

Ex:
The Apple Macintosh family of products consists of the product lines:
- Mac mini
- MacBook Pro
- Mac Pro

A product line is a grouping of products that are closely related in usage, functionality or marketing characteristics.

A Product Family typically is created to address one or five functions:

1. To increase profits and not erode the sales of existing products

2. To attract additional Markets or Market Segments

3. To counter competitor's products

4. To fill a gap in an existing Product Family.

5. To promote sales of other products in the family line

Line Depth refers to the number of products in the product line.

Line consistency refers to how closely related the products are that make up the product line.

Line vulnerability refers to the percentage of sales or profits that are derived from only a few products in the product line.

Product width refers to the number of different product lines sold by a company.

Product mix refers to the total number of products sold in all product lines.

Line extension refers to the adding of a new product to a line.

"Trading up or brand leveraging" refers to adding a product of better quality to a product line than the other products in that line.

"Trading down" refers to adding a product of lesser quality to a product line than the other products in that line.

If a line of products is sold with the same brand name, this is referred to as family branding.
Strategy and decisions regarding a product line are usually incorporated in a high-level marketing plan addressing product line strategy, sales, channels, distribution channels, pricing and related issues.
A product-line manager is responsible for a product line and supervises several product managers who are responsible for individual products within the line.
Product-line managers typically have the following responsibilities:
- Expansion and composition of a product line
- Evaluate the effects of product mixes on the profitability of other items in the line
- Planning and allocation of resources to individual products in the line
A product is normally associated with a brand strategy - manufacturer, private or generic.

1. Manufacturer-  or 'national' branding in which the brand is assigned by the manufacturer of the Product.

2. Private - or 'dealer' branding in which the brand is assigned by the retailer or wholesaler of the Product.

3. Generic - in which the Product is not marked with any identification.   Generic brands are a means for manufacturers to increase profits by saving on advertising, packaging or other costs associated with manufacturer or private branding.

A brand is name, term, sign, symbol or design or a combination of these which identify the goods or services and differentiate them from those of competitors'

A Trade mark is a brand or some part of the brand that is given legal protection because it is capable of exclusive appropriation and representation.

Manufacturers can use their own brands (known as Manufacturers' brands) or brands of their distributors (Distributors' brands).

Manufacturers/ distributors use brand names for a variety of reasons ranging from simple identification purposes to having legal protection for unique features of the products from imitations.

Brands help consumers recognize certain quality parameters. In some cases, brands are just used to endow the product with unique story and character which itself can be a basis for product differentiation.

Individual brands have their own identity and the corporate or common name is not used to promote its equity.

Individual branding requires more expensive advertising and brand extensive brand creation investments.  By extension, each new brand does not benefit from the positive perceptions of earlier brands.

By contrast, family branding has several advantages.

Each new product is quickly associated with the other products and brand in terms of quality and benefits.

Reduced or eliminated time for name identification and advertising for name recognition purposes.

Columns.Description: The name of the Product, which normally corresponds to the 'marketing name' of the Product.

Columns.Description: The name of the Product, which normally corresponds to the 'marketing name' of the Product.

Columns.Description: The internal code name by which the Product is known within the company.

Columns.Name: ProductIntendedUse
Columns.Description: The intended use of the product.

Columns.Name: IntroductionDate
Columns.Description: The date that the Product was introduced for sale.

Columns.Name: FirstDateManufactured
Columns.Description: The date that the Product was first manufactured by the Manufacturer.

Columns.Name: PlannedAbandonmentDate
Columns.Description:
The planned date to discontinue marketing the product.    

Abandonment is a component in the decline stage of the product's life cycle characterized by a reduced market demand for the product and an increased number of competing products with similar characteristics.

There are three (3) strategies for abandoning a product:

(1)  Reduced marketing and expenditures to maintain profits.

(2)  Concentrating on the strongest market segments and eliminating the weaker market segments

(3)  Maintain the marketing level until the product is discontinued.

Columns.Name: ActualAbandonmentDate
Columns.Description:
The actual date that the marketing of the product was discontinued. 

Abandonment is a component in the decline stage of the product's life cycle characterized by a reduced market demand for the product and an increased number of competing products with similar characteristics.

There are three (3) strategies for abandoning a product:

(1)  Reduced marketing and expenditures to maintain profits.

(2)  Concentrating on the strongest market segments and eliminating the weaker market segments

(3)  Maintain the marketing level until the product is discontinued.

Columns.Name: GlobalTradeItemNumber
Columns.Description:
The Global Trade Item Number (GTIN) is an identifier for trade items that was developed by GS1.

A GTIN can be assigned to only one brick.

Columns.Name: GtinName
Columns.Description: A note, comment or additional information regarding the Product GTIN.

Columns.Name: EuropeanArticleNumber
Columns.Description:
A 13 digit barcoding standard which is a superset of the original 12-digit Universal Product Code (UPC).

aka International Article Number (abbreviation of EAN retained)

Columns.Name: UniversalProductCode
Columns.Description:
A system that identifies products by type and by manufacturer.  

A UPC consists of eleven (11) digits.  Six (6) indicate the Manufacturer and five (5) digits describe the product.

UPCs appear on product packages as bar codes, which are graphic symbols that are read by optical scanner devices.   

UPCs are assigned by the Uniform Code Council of Dayton, Ohio.

Columns.Name: GpcBrickId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a GPC Brick.

Columns.Name: ItemElectronicProductCode
Columns.Description:
EPC is the RFID version of the UPC barcode. 
EPC is intended to be used for specific product identification. However, EPC goes beyond UPC by not only identifying the product as an SKU, but also providing access to additional data about the origin and history of the specific units. 
The EPC tag itself identifies the manufacturer, product, version, and serial number. It's the serial number that takes EPC to the next level. 
This is the key to data related to specific lots/batches as well as potentially tracking the specific unit's history as it moves through the supply chain.

Columns.Name: ComponentPartIdentifier
Columns.Description: The Component / Part Identifier (CPID) is used to identify components or parts that are used in the assembly of a larger item. The CPID is part of the GS1 system of standards.

Columns.Name: PluCode
Columns.Description:
The PLU or Price Look-Up code is a 4- or 5-digit number that is primarily used on fresh produce items and will typically appear on a small sticker that is applied to an individual piece of fresh produce. 

The PLU code identifies produce items based upon the commodity, variety and size group. 

They are used by supermarkets to make check-out and inventory control easier, faster and more accurate. 

These numbers are assigned by the International Federation for Produce Standards (IFPS)

Ex: WHITE FLESH PEACHES
PLU Code = 4400

Columns.Description: A health claim regarding the product as per regulations of the target market.

Columns.Description: A market message that is present on the packaging of the product.

Columns.Description: Indicates whether a Product is comprised of a bundle of other Products.

Columns.Description: The label text that identifies the care, use, preparation and handling or the product.

Columns.Name: DescriptiveLabelText
Columns.Description: The label text that describes significant characteristics and benefits.

Columns.Name: WarningInformationText
Columns.Description: The text of the warning label, if any, appearing upon the product.

Columns.Name: GradeLabelText
Columns.Description:
The label text that identifies Product quality with letters, number or conditions.

Examples:

-  Grade A
-  Prime
-  #1

Columns.Name: GovernmentWarningLabelText
Columns.Description: The US Government (or foreign government) label text that addressing the US legal requirements of the Product.

Columns.Name: PatentNumber

Columns.Description: The date that the Patent was granted.

Columns.Name: PatentExpirationDate
Columns.Description: The date that the patent is scheduled to expire.

Columns.Name: Trademark
Columns.Description: A 'trademark' is a brand name or brand mark that is given legal protection.

Columns.Name: ProductLogo

Columns.Name: ProductSymbol
Columns.Description: A symbol by which the product is known.

Columns.Name: CopyrightNumber

The unique identifier (number) of the copyright granted.

A copyright is legal protection given to a work so that it can only be published or sold by the copyright holder.

Columns.Name: CopyrightDate
Columns.Description: The date that the copyright was granted.

Columns.Name: ProductLicenserName
Columns.Description: The name of the company that receives a flat fee or royalty for selling the rights to use a trademark, Patent, manufacturing right or process for the Product.

Columns.Name: EligibleForExportIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the product is eligible for export to foreign countries without restriction.

Columns.Name: ProductExportRestrictionIndicator

Columns.Name: ProductExportRestrictionEndDate

Columns.Name: ProductExportRestrictionDescription

Properties.Description:
A product is anything that can be offered to a market that might satisfy a want or need by potential customers.    That product is the sum of all physical, psychological, symbolic, and service attributes associated with it.

There are two basic types of products:

- Tangible (physical)
- Intangible (non-physical) such as services

A service is a non-material or intangible product - such as professional consultancy, maintenance service, repair service etc.
Each product has its own benefits, application, brand name, and packaging that gives it its own identity and distinguishing characteristics.

Every business or organization has business rules that define precisely what a product is.    While we intuitively know what a product is, we must quantify that knowledge and associated business rules with consistent definitions that can be implemented within the organization in strategies and applications.

A product typically goes through five stages of development:

(1) Idea Stage - involving a thorough evaluation of the potential product

(2) Concept Stage - determines customer acceptance by testing and presentation to consumers and distribution channel members.   Specific aspects regarding quality, dependability, reliability, warranty, packaging, service, pricing, terms of sale, sales and distribution channels, advertising and promotions are evaluated.

(3) Product Development Stage - transforms the prototype product into an actual product for mass sale.   This stage requires close interaction between both marketing and manufacturing.

(4) Test Marketing Stage - may or may not be used since it is an expensive and time-consuming process.  Test marketing involves evaluating various product options and alternatives.

(5) Commercialization - It is very expensive to launch a new product so commercialization only applies to those specific products that are actually going to be sold to the market.

Products tend to be categorized as either:  Industrial goods and consumer goods

Industrial goods are used to produce other products .

Industrial goods may be further divided into:

- Raw materials
- Equipment
- Pre-built materials 
- Supplies.

Consumer goods are intended for consumption by the general public.

Consumer goods may be further divided into:

- Durable goods
- Nondurable goods
- Packaged goods

A product may be a member of a product family or product line.

A product family is a grouping of products or services that are related to each other by common function, functionality, design platform or similar characteristics.

Members of a product family frequently have many common parts and assemblies.

Product families are the highest level of grouping for forecasting, capacity planning or related functions.

Ex:
The Apple Macintosh family of products consists of the product lines:
- Mac mini
- MacBook Pro
- Mac Pro

A product line is a grouping of products that are closely related in usage, functionality or marketing characteristics.

A Product Family typically is created to address one or five functions:

1. To increase profits and not erode the sales of existing products

2. To attract additional Markets or Market Segments

3. To counter competitor's products

4. To fill a gap in an existing Product Family.

5. To promote sales of other products in the family line

Line Depth refers to the number of products in the product line.

Line consistency refers to how closely related the products are that make up the product line.

Line vulnerability refers to the percentage of sales or profits that are derived from only a few products in the product line.

Product width refers to the number of different product lines sold by a company.

Product mix refers to the total number of products sold in all product lines.

Line extension refers to the adding of a new product to a line.

"Trading up or brand leveraging" refers to adding a product of better quality to a product line than the other products in that line.

"Trading down" refers to adding a product of lesser quality to a product line than the other products in that line.

If a line of products is sold with the same brand name, this is referred to as family branding.
Strategy and decisions regarding a product line are usually incorporated in a high-level marketing plan addressing product line strategy, sales, channels, distribution channels, pricing and related issues.
A product-line manager is responsible for a product line and supervises several product managers who are responsible for individual products within the line.
Product-line managers typically have the following responsibilities:
- Expansion and composition of a product line
- Evaluate the effects of product mixes on the profitability of other items in the line
- Planning and allocation of resources to individual products in the line
A product is normally associated with a brand strategy - manufacturer, private or generic.

1. Manufacturer-  or 'national' branding in which the brand is assigned by the manufacturer of the Product.

2. Private - or 'dealer' branding in which the brand is assigned by the retailer or wholesaler of the Product.

3. Generic - in which the Product is not marked with any identification.   Generic brands are a means for manufacturers to increase profits by saving on advertising, packaging or other costs associated with manufacturer or private branding.

A brand is name, term, sign, symbol or design or a combination of these which identify the goods or services and differentiate them from those of competitors'

A Trade mark is a brand or some part of the brand that is given legal protection because it is capable of exclusive appropriation and representation.

Manufacturers can use their own brands (known as Manufacturers' brands) or brands of their distributors (Distributors' brands).

Manufacturers/ distributors use brand names for a variety of reasons ranging from simple identification purposes to having legal protection for unique features of the products from imitations.

Brands help consumers recognize certain quality parameters. In some cases, brands are just used to endow the product with unique story and character which itself can be a basis for product differentiation.

Individual brands have their own identity and the corporate or common name is not used to promote its equity.

Individual branding requires more expensive advertising and brand extensive brand creation investments.  By extension, each new brand does not benefit from the positive perceptions of earlier brands.

By contrast, family branding has several advantages.

Each new product is quickly associated with the other products and brand in terms of quality and benefits.

Reduced or eliminated time for name identification and advertising for name recognition purposes.

NewEntity.Name: Country
NewEntity.Description:
The Country definition is based upon ISO 3166 Country Codes:

Each country or territory has three codes:
-  a two letter code 
-  a three letter code 
-  a three digit code

The numeric code identifies a physical territory, and the letters a country name. Thus when Germany reunified, it kept DE/DEU but changed from 280 to 276, while when Southern Rhodesia was renamed Zimbabwe it stayed 716 but changed from RH/RHO to ZW/ZWE.

Codes withdrawn from use may not be reused for five years. The two letter codes AA, QM to QZ, XA to XZ, and ZZ, all three letter codes beginning with those pairs, and numeric codes beginning 9, are available for individual use and will not be allocated to countries. The codes OO, OOO, and 000 are designated for use as "escape codes" to indicate that additional codes are being used.

The term "country" is perhaps a little misleading: not all the "countries" in ISO 3166 are actually independent.   Many of them are geographically separate territories that are legally portions or dependencies of other countries. Nonetheless the term "country" is used throughout. Where the code for a country includes territory also included in another code, a code for the exclusive part can be formed by replacing the second and third letters by X. 

ISO 3166 was first issued in 1974, and the three digit numbers were mostly added in 1981.

Changes to ISO 3166 are managed by the ISO 3166 Maintenance Agency (ISO3166/MA).

Examples of ISO 3166 codes:

CA CAN 124 Canada
US USA 840 United States of America

Where the code for a country includes territory also included in another code, a code for the exclusive part can be formed by replacing the second and third letters by X.

NewEntity.Name: DirectEmissionsFromRefrigeration
NewEntity.Description:
This guidance document addresses the following:

- Emissions from users of refrigeration and air conditioning equipment including household refrigeration, domestic air conditioning and heat pumps, mobile air conditioning, chillers, retail food refrigeration, cold storage warehouses, refrigerated transport, industrial process refrigeration, and commercial unitary air conditioning systems.

- Emissions from fixed and portable fire suppression equipment.

- Direct emissions from purchased industrial gases. These gases can be used in processes such as manufacturing, testing, or laboratory applications.

Emissions from the refrigeration and air conditioning sector result from the manufacturing process, from leakage and service over the operational life of the equipment, and from disposal at the end of the useful life of the equipment.

This only applies to scope 1 GHG emissions resulting from operations at the reporting organization's facilities.

For refrigeration, air conditioning, and fire suppression equipment, these emissions may take place during the installation, use, or disposal. Refrigerants and fire suppressants may be released from equipment leaks throughout their operating life or from catastrophic leaks. Also, when equipment is installed, repaired, or removed, refrigerants and fire suppressants may be released if proper recovery processes are not used. Fire suppressants are also emitted to extinguish fires. Emissions that occur during the manufacturing or disposal of equipment or purchased gases are scope 3 indirect emissions, and are not included in an organization's scope 1 emissions. 

Four methods with varying levels of accuracy and data collection required are outlined in this guidance to calculate GHG emissions. Organizations may calculate fugitive GHG emissions from refrigeration and air conditioning equipment, fire suppression systems, or purchased industrial gases with one of the following methods.

NewEntity.Name: FacilityType
NewEntity.Description:
A categorization of stores based upon common characteristics or functionality.

Ex:
- Central Business District
- Community Center
- Convenience Store
- Discount Store
- Discount-Anchored Center
- Gas Station
- Neighborhood Center
- Pad Site 
- Power Shopping Center
- Regional Center
- Strip Center
- Superstore 
- Warehouse Club
- Warehouse Store

where:

CENTRAL BUSINESS DISTRICT
 The traditional downtown business area of a city or town.
 
COMMUNITY CENTER
 A large shopping center that includes a discount store, specialty department store, super drugstore, home-improvement center and other convenience and shopping goods stores.
 
CONVENIENCE STORE
 A shopping center that typically includes such stores as a convenience store and a dry cleaner.
 
DISCOUNT STORE
 A general merchandise retailer offering a wide variety of merchandise,  limited service and low prices:

Ex:
- Target 
- Kmart
 
DISCOUNT-ANCHORED CENTER
 A shopping center that contains one or more discount stores plus smaller retail tenants.
 
NEIGHBORHOOD CENTER
 A shopping center that includes a supermarket, drugstore, home-improvement center or variety store.  

Neighborhood centers often include small stores, such as apparel, shoe, camera and other shopping goods stores.
 
PAD SITE
 A location for a free-standing retail building that sits in front of a mall or shopping center.
 
POWER SHOPPING CENTER
 A large, open-air shopping center with the majority of space pre-leased to several well-known anchor retail tenants.  

Convenient access and parking are emphasized.  These centers usually sit on major intersections.
 
REGIONAL CENTER
 A shopping center or mall which includes up to three department stores plus shopping or specialty stores rather than convenience stores.  
Super-regionals are similar but have at least four department stores.
 
STRIP CENTER
 A small shopping center that comprises several adjacent stores located along a major street or highway.
 
SUPERSTORE A large supermarket or specialty store, usually between 20,000 and 100,000 square feet.
 
WAREHOUSE CLUB
 A retail store that sells a limited assortment of general merchandise to customers who are members of the club. Memberships are generally fee-based, margins are small and there is little customer service provided to the members.
 
WAREHOUSE STORE
 A discount retailer offering merchandise in a no-frills environment.

A location is a physical point that can be defined as a single latitude / longitude. A location can be used to describe:

- the address of a physical structure
- the location of a business or service
- the location of a component
- the delivery location for a shipment or mail

Columns.Name: LocationState
Columns.Description:
The unique identifier of the State = State Code.

A two-digit FIPS code assigned by the NIST to identify each State and statistically equivalent entity. The NIST assigns the codes based on the alphabetic sequence of State names (Puerto Rico and the Outlying Areas appear at the end); it documents these codes in a FIPS publication (FIPS PUB 5). Also, a two-digit code assigned by the Census Bureau to identify each State within its census geographic division (Puerto Rico and the Outlying Areas appear at the end).

Properties.Description:
Market-based method: A method to quantify the scope 2 GHG emissions of a reporter based on GHG emissions emitted by the generators from which the reporter contractually purchases electricity bundled with contractual instruments, or contractual instruments on their own.

Market-based: Where we have options in terms of energy product or supplier, these are the emissions associated with our procurement choices in the market.

NewEntity.Name: PaymentCard
NewEntity.Description:
A payment card enables card holders to purchase products or services without cash and to pay for them at a later date or with the value associated with the payment card related account or it's stored value.

Typically in order to qualify for this type of credit, the card holder must open an account with a bank or company, which sponsors a card. 

The card holder then receives a line of credit with a specified dollar amount.   They can use the card to make purchases from participating merchants until they reach this credit limit. 

Every month the sponsor provides a bill, which aggregates the card activity during the previous 30 days. Depending on the terms of the card, the customer may pay interest charges on the amount that they do not pay for on a monthly basis.  

The banks and companies that provide or sponsor payment cards profit in three ways. 

(1)  They make money from the interest payments charged on the unpaid balance

(2)  They also can make money by charging an annual fee for the use of the card

(3)  The sponsors make money by charging merchants a small percentage of income for the service of the card. This arrangement is acceptable to the merchants because they can let their customers pay by payment card instead of requiring cash. 

The merchant makes arrangements to participate in a payment card program with a merchant bank, which in turn works with a card-issuing bank. The merchant bank determines what percentage of the total purchase value has to be paid by the merchant to the card-issuing bank. The amount varies depending on the volume and type of business, but in general it is between 1-2%. A percentage of that amount is kept by the merchant bank as a transaction-processing fee.

NewEntity.Name: PaymentCardAcquisitionMethod
NewEntity.Description:
The method by which the payment card information was obtained from the payment card presented by the individual.

Ex.:
- Swipe
- Dip
- Tap
- Manual
- Impression

where: 
- Swipe occurs when the payment card is swiped and the magnetic stripe along the side of the card is read to obtain the payment card information
- Dip occurs when the payment card is inserted, usually, at the bottom of the card so that payment card information can be obtained from the chip embedded in the payment card
- Tap occurs when the payment card is tapped for the payment card information to be obtained. Payment card information is generally obtained using RFID technology, for devices such as smart phones using apple pay, google pay or similar applications the payment card information is obtained using NFC technology which belongs to a small subset of the RFID technology family.
- Manual occurs when payment card information was provided over the phone or in person
- Impression occurs when an impression of the payment card was taken

Columns.Name: PaymentAccountNumber
Columns.Description:
The number of the payment card. It is also referred to as the Primary Account Number (PAN) = The number that is embossed, encoded, or both, on a plastic card that identifies the issuer and the particular cardholder account.

The account number on the card, which is unique to every cardholder. The card number is used to identify the purchaser for authorization and billing purposes.

The Payment Card Industry (PCI) Data Security Standard (DSS) requires that the PAN be stored with strong encryption at all times and masked whenever it is displayed.

Credit card numbers are a special case of ISO/IEC 7812 bank card numbers.
An ISO/IEC 7812 number contains a single-digit Major Industry Identifier (MII), a six-digit Issuer Identification Number (IIN), an account number, and a single digit check sum calculated using the Luhn algorithm. The MII is considered to be part of the IIN.
The card number's prefix is the sequence of digits at the beginning of the number that determine the credit card network to which the number belongs.

The first digit of your credit card number is the Major Industry Identifier (MII), which represents the category of entity which issued your credit card. Different MII digits represent the following issuer categories:

MII Digit Value Issuer Category

1 Airlines
2 Airlines and other industry assignments
3 Travel and entertainment
4 Banking and financial
5 Banking and financial
6 Merchandizing and banking
7 Petroleum
8 Telecommunications and other industry assignments
9 National assignment

Issuer Identification Number
The first 6 digits of the credit card number are known as the Issuer Identification Number (IIN). These identify the institution that issued the card to the card holder. The rest of the number is allocated by the issuer.

Digits 7 to (n - 1) of your credit card number are your individual account identifier. The maximum length of a credit card number is 19 digits. Since the initial 6 digits of a credit card number are the issuer identifier, and the final digit is the check digit, this means that the maximum length of the account number field is 19 - 7, or 12 digits.

Card Length
American Express = 15
Discover Card = 16
MasterCard = 16
Visa = 13 or 16

Columns.Name: PaymentCardCardholderName
Columns.Description: The name of a Payment Card Cardholder.

Columns.Name: PaymentCardExpirationDate
Columns.Description: The last day of the designated month/year the credit card is valid.

Columns.Name: PaymentCardServiceCode
Columns.Description: Three-digit or four-digit value in the magnetic-stripe that follows the expiration date of the payment card on the track data. It is used for various things such as defining service attributes, differentiating between international and national interchange, or identifying usage restrictions.

Columns.Name: IssuingBankId
Columns.Description:
The unique identifier of an Issuer.

The first 6 digits of the credit card number are known as the Issuer Identification Number (IIN). These identify the institution that issued the card to the card holder.

Columns.Name: PaymentCardFullTrackData
Columns.Description: Also referred to as "track data" or "magnetic-stripe data." Data encoded in the magnetic stripe or chip used for authentication and/or authorization during payment transactions. Can be the magnetic-stripe image on a chip or the data on the track 1 and/or track 2 portion of the magnetic stripe.

Columns.Name: PaymentCardCvc2CardValidationCode
Columns.Description:
Card Validation Code - MasterCard term for the three-digit code printed next to the card number in the signature panel and used as part of the authorization process.

The Payment Card Industry (PCI) Data Security Standard (DSS) requires that the CVC2 only be stored for the purpose of authorizing a transaction. Once a transaction has been authorized the CVC2 data must be deleted.

Columns.Name: PaymentCardCvvCardVerificationValue
Columns.Description:
Card Verification Value - Visa term for the three-digit code printed next to the card number in the signature panel and used as part of the authorization process.

The Payment Card Industry (PCI) Data Security Standard (DSS) requires that the CVV only be stored for the purpose of authorizing a transaction. Once a transaction has been authorized the CVV data must be deleted.

Columns.Name: PaymentCardPin
Columns.Description: Acronym for "personal identification number." Secret numeric password known only to the user and a system to authenticate the user to the system. The user is only granted access if the PIN the user provided matches the PIN in the system. Typical PINs are used for automated teller machines for cash advance transactions. Another type of PIN is one used in EMV chip cards where the PIN replaces the cardholder's signature.

Columns.Name: PaymentCardPinBlock
Columns.Description: A block of data used to encapsulate a PIN during processing. The PIN block format defines the content of the PIN block and how it is processed to retrieve the PIN. The PIN block is composed of the PIN, the PIN length, and may contain subset of the PAN.

The Payment Card Industry (PCI) Data Security Standard (DSS) requires that the PAN be stored with strong encryption at all times and masked whenever it is displayed.

Credit card numbers are a special case of ISO/IEC 7812 bank card numbers.
An ISO/IEC 7812 number contains a single-digit Major Industry Identifier (MII), a six-digit Issuer Identification Number (IIN), an account number, and a single digit check sum calculated using the Luhn algorithm. The MII is considered to be part of the IIN.
The card number's prefix is the sequence of digits at the beginning of the number that determine the credit card network to which the number belongs.

The first digit of your credit card number is the Major Industry Identifier (MII), which represents the category of entity which issued your credit card. Different MII digits represent the following issuer categories:

1 Airlines

3 Travel and entertainment
4 Banking and financial

7 Petroleum
8 Telecommunications and other industry assignments
9 National assignment

Issuer Identification Number

Digits 7 to (n - 1) of your credit card number are your individual account identifier. The maximum length of a credit card number is 19 digits. Columns.Description: The electronic serial number is a unique identification number embedded by manufacturers on a microchip in their product. While the ESN was first commonly used in wireless phones it has found traction in other electronic products.

Columns.Name: GlobalIndividualAssetIdentifier
Columns.Description: The Global Individual Asset Identifier (GIAI) is a simple tool used to identify an asset by type, uniquely where required. The GIAI is part of the GS1 system of standards.

Columns.Name: GlobalReturnableAssetIdentifier
Columns.Description:
The Global Returnable Asset Identifier (GRAI) was developed by GS1 to be used to identify assets by type. It can also be used to uniquely identify assets by including the serial number. 

The GRAI is used to identify Returnable Transport Items (RTI) such as pallets, roll container, crates. The GRAI identifies the type of returnable asset.

Columns.Description: The timestamp that the Transaction was confirmed to the Customer/Customer Account.

Columns.Name: CreditCheckTimestamp
Columns.Description: The timestamp that the Customer/Customer Account had a credit check in regard to the Transaction amount.

Columns.Name: RequestedDeliveryDate
Columns.Description: The date that the Customer/Customer Account requested delivery of the items.

Columns.Name: CommittedDeliveryDate
Columns.Description: The date committed to the Customer/Customer Account for delivery of the items.

Columns.Name: ActualDeliveryTimestamp
Columns.Description: The actual timestamp of delivery of the items to the Customer/Customer Account.

Columns.Name: DeliveryConfirmationTimestamp
Columns.Description: The timestamp that confirmation of the delivery or Shipment was made to the Customer/Customer Account.

Columns.Name: TransactionAmount
Columns.Description:
The amount associated with the transaction.

Ex:
Refund = 'amount'
Credit = 'amount'

Columns.Name: ShipmentToName
Columns.Description: The name of the ship-to party.

Columns.Name: ShipmentToLocationId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Location.

Columns.Name: TransactionConfirmationNumber
Columns.Description: The transaction confirmation number provided to confirm that the transaction was executed.

Columns.Name: IdentificationCheckedIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates whether the individual's identification was checked for any requirements for the transaction. For example: The individual is 21 years of age or older in order to purchase alcohol products.

Columns.Name: IdentificationId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of the identification.

Columns.Name: TotalRetailPriceAmount
Columns.Description: The total list price value of the Transaction products = (list price per unit product price)x(quantity ordered) for each line item.

Columns.Name: TotalAdjustmentPercentage
Columns.Description: The total percentage of adjustment(s) applied to the Transaction.

Columns.Name: TotalAdjustmentAmount
Columns.Description: The total amount of adjustments applied to the Transaction.

Columns.Name: TotalTransactionSalesPriceAmount
Columns.Description: The total actual price value of the transaction item(s) = (actual selling price per unit product price)x(quantity) for each line item.

Columns.Name: TotalShippingChargeAmount
Columns.Description: The total amount of shipping charge associated with the Transaction.

Columns.Name: TransactionTotalTaxAmount
Columns.Description: The total amount of all taxes applied to the Transaction.

Columns.Name: TransactionRoundingAmount
Columns.Description: The amount of rounding applied to the transaction. This is typically done when the payment method is cash and the total invoice amount is rounded to an amount that is payable using legal tender. (e.g. 1 cent coin is no longer in legal circulation.)

Columns.Name: TransactionTotalInvoicedAmount
Columns.Description: The total invoiced amount to the Customer/Customer Account.

Columns.Name: TotalCommissionsPayableAmount
Columns.Description: The total amount of commissions payable and due in regard to the Transaction.

Columns.Name: SplitCommissionsIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the commissions are to be split between two or more employees.

Columns.Name: RequestedShipmentCarrierName
Columns.Description: The name of the Carrier for the Shipment requested by the Customer/Customer Account.

Columns.Name: AlternateCarrierAcceptableIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that an alternate Carrier of the Shipment would be acceptable to the Customer/Customer Account.

Columns.Name: ShipCompleteIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the Transaction item(s) are only to be shipped when complete - no partial shipments.

Columns.Name: AcknowledgementRequiredIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that an acknowledgement  to the Customer/Customer Account is required for the Transaction.

Columns.Name: ExpediteTransactionIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the Transaction is to be expedited.

Columns.Name: DropShipmentIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the Transaction item(s) are to be drop shipped.
